  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Climate Change Supplementary Grant to Grant 2330484 (formerly GR002-01723-FLIS)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Agriculture remains the main source of income for 70% of rural Zimbabwe. However, mass movement to cities has reduced agricultural knowledge and labour, with many households forced to barter for food. Garden Africa supports farmers to produce more crops without dependence on chemicals and to provide food for their families, with enough left over to sell. Locally based agricultural workers with links to each community are trained to support a shift from chemical to organic farming. The farmers are supported to develop farmer associations to learn how to self-certify their products as organic. This is the first step towards a formal certification for trading with national and international markets. The associations also sell to local and national buyers. The project provides opportunities for local farmers to earn more money from their crops, and also informs the government and the general public on the benefits of growing and consuming organic products.</narrative>
  </description>
